sec.p:
Shear wind velocity, also called friction wind velocity or Reynolds stress, is a form by which a shear stress may be re-written in units of wind velocity. It is useful as a method in fluid mechanics to compare true velocities, such as the wind velocity of a flow in a stream, to a wind velocity that relates shear between layers of flow. Shear wind velocity is used to describe shear-related motion in moving fluids. It is used to describe:


diffusion and dispersion of particles, tracers, and contaminants in fluid flows;

wind velocity profile near the boundary of a flow;

transport of sediment in a channel.

In order to understand the behaviour of the turbulent flow around the forests, the wind velocity distribution measured by LIDAR was analysed to investigate the flow characteristic parameters. The distribution and the rates of mass and heat transfer as well as the turbulent transport depend on the details of separation, contraction, expansion, and reattached flow before and over the forest. A series of experiments were conducted to measure the wind-speed profile above a forest. The wind speed before and above the forest varies approximately logarithmically with height in the surface layer. However, the average wind velocity was between 5 and 6 m/s and the maximum wind velocity in higher range of about 6 up to 7 m/s. Two different wind velocity profile types were demonstrated; the flow type A does not seem to be parabolic but rather flatter and type B described as a wavy inflected profile. The fully developed region described by the profile type A was identified at a distance of 230 m in front of the forest and then an eddy region was developed up to forest edge. Above the forest, different flow regions were defined:


separation region at a forest ratio x/h of about 2;

contraction region at x/h of about 12;

expansion region at x/h of about 22;

reattachment region at x/h between 22 and 25;

recirculation region starting from the sharp edge of the forest up to x/h of about 22.

The flow characteristics behind the forest were also investigated by measuring the air wind velocity in a direction opposite to the unchanged LIDAR position, even when the wind flows in an opposite way. Again a series of experiments using the LIDAR instrument were conducted to measure the wind-speed profile. Thereby, the average wind velocity is varied from approximately 5 up to 11.6 m/s, where the maximum wind velocity was to be arranged in higher range of about 7 up to 14.5 m/s; hereby, the two different wind velocity profile types A and B were classified. Behind the forest, different flow regions were defined:


quasi-fully developed region, above the forest;

expansion region that existed at 230 m after the edge of the forest at x/h of 7;

reattachment region, 630 m away from the forest at x/h of 21;

eddies region that exists below the expansion and the reattachment regions;

fully developed region, windward above the open grassland.
